data.value:
The Accumulation/Distribution (A/D) indicator is a cumulative tool that uses volume and price to evaluate the accumulation or distribution of a stock. A/D measures the discrepancies between price and volume, which helps determine the strength of the current trend. If prices are rising but A/D is falling, this may indicate there is not enough volume to support growth and prices are likely to decline.

Calculation:
A certain amount of the candle volume is added to or subtracted from the current accumulated value of the indicator. The closer the closing price is to the high of the candle, the greater the added amount. The closer the closing price is to the low of the candle, the larger the amount to be subtracted. If the closing price is strictly between the maximum and minimum, the value of the indicator does not change.
A/D (i) = ((CLOSE (i) — LOW (i))-(HIGH (i)-CLOSE (i)) * VOLUME (i)/(HIGH (i)-the LOW (i)) A/D (i-1)
Where is:
A/D (i) — is the value of the accumulation/distribution Indicator for the current bar;
Close (i) — is the closing price of the bar;
Low (i) — is the minimum price of the bar;
High(i) — is the maximum price of the bar;
Volume (i) — is the volume;
A/D (i-1) — is the value of the accumulation/distribution Indicator for the previous bar.

